    "Matthew Henry": ",\n29. Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` herein did neither disc bey God, who bid him contend with Sihon, nor dissemble with Sihon; but doubtless it was by divine direction that he did it, that Sihon might be left inexcusable, though God hardened his heart. Tliis may illustrate the method c^f God's dealing with those to wh'm he gives his gospel, but does net give grace to believe it.",
    "Rudolf Schnackenburg, Sharon Pace": "), the expulsion of the demons into the herd of swine and the destruction of the swine in the waters of the lake (vv. 30-32), the swineherds' report in the city, and the request of the citizenry that he leave their neighborhood (vv. 33-34). The peculiarities in Matthew are two possessed persons instead of Mark's one (cf. our Intro., p. 4); \"suddenly\" (\nv. 29); \"at some distance\" (\nv. 29, \"your Father\"; vv. 32-33, \"my Father in heaven\") underscore this, and bring the passage up-to-date for the disciples and for the Matthean community. 26-27 The common Synoptic expression of\nv. 29) and, especially, the climactic sentence on the bursting in of the Reign of God through Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`' expulsion of demons (\nv. 29). In the preparation for the feeding, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`' disciples are included only incidentally. Their question, \"Where are we to get enough bread?\" is a narrative figure indicating Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` as the provider (cf. John `[char_John_Ref]` 6:5-7). 36-38 The blessing of the bread, its distribution to the people by the disciples, the multitude having its fill, and the leftover pieces are all recounted in a manner similar to that of the first feeding. Mark's separate blessing and distribution of the fish are abbreviated by Matthew and absorbed into the treatment of the bread (\n29. Matthew does not explicitly identify the prayer, but presumes it in the concluding clause ("
