    "Rudolf Schnackenburg, Sharon Pace": "goes beyond the summons to give and to lend - granted, with the application of elements from the Lukan text (Luke 6:30, 35). Inasmuch as no bases are offered for the required behavior, an understanding of the sense of this antithesis is especially difficult and has led to extremely diverse interpretations, with far-reaching consequences for practical conduct. 38-39a The shorter opening formula, once more (as in w. 27 and 43), introduces a principle that in Exodus 21:24, Leviticus 24:20, and Deuteronomy 19:21 is formulated for the right of equal retribution (the so-called ius talionis). Matthew sets forth this view of the law, which itself was intended to prevent legitimate retribution from becoming revenge, before he gives us the traditional words of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`. He sees the new element as \"do not resist\" the one who injures you. 39b-41 The three cases here (the third,"
